# Feature Architecture (2026 STRICT CONTRACT)

This file defines how features must be structured internally and how they interact with the rest of the system.

A feature is a **self-contained domain module** with explicit internal layering and strict ownership rules.

---

# 1. Core Principle

A feature is an isolated business domain unit.

Rule:
- features are self-contained systems
- features do not depend on other features
- features only communicate through shared abstractions or external services

---

# 2. Feature Internal Architecture (MANDATORY STRUCTURE)

Every feature MUST follow a consistent internal structure:

## Required structure

features/[domain]/
  components/
  hooks/
  services/
  model/
  utils/
  types/
  index.ts

Alternative allowed (UI-heavy features):

features/[domain]/
  ui/
  hooks/
  services/
  state/
  types/
  index.ts

Rule:
- deviation from structure requires explicit justification
- arbitrary file organization is forbidden

---

# 3. Internal Dependency Direction (STRICT)

Inside every feature:

ui → hooks → services → model/utils → types

Rules:
- UI can use hooks
- hooks can use services
- services can use model/utils
- model/utils must be pure and UI-agnostic

Forbidden:
- services importing UI
- utils importing hooks
- UI importing services directly without hooks layer (except simple read-only cases)

---

# 4. Feature Isolation Rule

- features must not import other features directly
- cross-feature reuse must go through shared/ or services layer
- feature-to-feature coupling is forbidden

Rule:
- each feature is an independent bounded context

---

# 5. Feature Entry Point Contract (STRICT)

Each feature must expose a controlled public API:

index.ts is the ONLY public entrypoint.

Rules:
- internal files are private by default
- no deep imports from outside the feature
- only index.ts is stable contract surface

---

# 6. Feature Composition Rule

- features are composed at page/app level only
- features must not compose other features internally
- shared composition logic must live in shared/ or app layer

Rule:
- composition happens above feature level, never inside peer features

---

# 7. Shared Layer Boundary Rule

- feature-specific logic must never be moved to shared/
- shared/ is only for domain-agnostic reuse
- duplication is preferred over premature extraction

Rule:
- if it is not reusable across domains, it stays in the feature

---

# 8. Feature Cohesion Rule

Each feature must represent a single cohesive domain concept.

Forbidden:
- mixing unrelated workflows in the same feature
- merging multiple business domains into one folder
- ambiguous feature boundaries

Rule:
- one feature = one domain responsibility

---

# 9. UI Boundaries Inside Feature

- UI inside feature is composition-only
- UI must not contain business logic
- UI state is allowed only if presentation-related

Rule:
- UI is render layer, not domain layer

---

# 10. Services Layer Rule

- services encapsulate domain operations and side effects
- services must not depend on UI
- services must be reusable within feature scope

Rule:
- services = domain interaction layer

---

# 11. Model Layer Rule

- model/ contains pure domain logic
- must be deterministic
- must not depend on React or UI state

Rule:
- model is framework-agnostic

---

# 12. Feature Size Control Rule

- avoid oversized features
- if a feature grows beyond single responsibility, it must be split

Indicators for split:
- unrelated workflows
- divergent UI patterns
- independent lifecycle domains

Rule:
- vertical scaling is preferred over horizontal mixing

---

# 13. Anti-Patterns (STRICT)

Forbidden patterns:

- feature importing another feature internally
- business logic inside UI components
- services importing UI layer
- utils depending on hooks or state
- multiple entrypoints per feature
- uncontrolled internal structure drift

---

# 14. System Guarantee

If respected:

- fully isolated domain modules
- predictable feature scaling
- controlled dependency graph
- clean separation UI / domain / infra
- maintainable large-scale frontend architecture